Disk Forensics > [T7]: User Device Access: Correlating GUIDs and Artifacts

(4) Which user accessed the device?

A quick reminder before we start, each user on the system has his NTUser.dat hive, JumpLists, LNK files, and ShellBags (i.e., they are not system-wide artifacts). Any connected device trace found in these artifacts means the corresponding user accessed that device.

To determine if a user accessed a specific device, you will use the device GUID for correlation. From a device perspective, GUID can be extracted from the "HKLM/SYSTEM/MountedDevices" under the SYSTEM hive. 

From a user perspective, the "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\MountPoints2" key will include a list of used devices GUIDs. 

By correlating the GUID between the two keys, you can confirm if a user used the device in one way or another.

NTUSER.dat MountPoints2 key (zoom in)

  1. MountPoints2 registry key.
  2. MountPoints2 registry key path.
  3. A list of GUID for devices that the user accessed. Remember the Volume GUID we extracted from the 'MountedDevices' key under the SYSTEM hive? By correlating GUID from both keys, you can validate which devices the user accessed.
In addition, we can utilize other user-specific artifacts to dig further and find out what objects the user accessed on a device, for example, by checking the VolumeInfoCache key in the SOFTWARE hive (mentioned above). We get the following information.

Microsoft\Windows Search\VolumeInfoCache key - (zoom in)
 

You can see that a USB device was mounted under two different letters, D and, E. Since both drives have the same name, we can assume that the same USB drive was connected twice, and assigned a different drive letter each time. The first time it was connected was on 2022-10-28 at 10:38:02 UTC. 

You can narrow down/filter what to search for in LNK files to create a user-to-device mapping using the "drive letter". To do so, using TimeLine Explorer, filter based on "working path,".

Filtering parsed lnk.csv in TimeLineExplorer (zoom in)
 
Using LNK files, you can confirm that the user accessed two directories on the connected device, 'Top Secret' and 'C-Levels.'
 
In the same way, you can use shellbags and JmpLists, to identify objects a user accessed on a particular device. These are different options to achieve the same thing. The bottom line, you can use user-specific artifacts to extract evidence of accessing objects on a particular device.
